**How to Implement Random Pivot (Optimization):**

To improve QuickSort's robustness and avoid the worst-case O(n^2) performance on sorted or nearly sorted arrays, you should select a random pivot.  Here's how you would modify the `partition` method:

```java
import java.util.Random;

// Add this at the class level:
private static final Random RANDOM = new Random();

private int partition(int[] arr, int low, int high) {
    // Choose a random pivot index
    int randomIndex = RANDOM.nextInt(high - low + 1) + low;
    swap(arr, randomIndex, high); // Swap random element with the last element (pivot)

    int pivot = arr[high]; // Last element is now the pivot

    int i = (low - 1);

    for (int j = low; j <= high - 1; j++) {
        if (arr[j] <= pivot) {
            i++;
            swap(arr, i, j);
        }
    }
    swap(arr, i + 1, high);
    return (i + 1);
}
```

By randomly selecting the pivot, the probability of consistently choosing a bad pivot is significantly reduced, resulting in much better average-case performance, and avoiding the O(n^2) worst-case.

