        System.out.println("Array: [5, 2, 9, 1, 5, 6], k = 3, Kth smallest (Quickselect): " + kthFinder.findKthSmallestQuickselect(arr6.clone(), k6));


        int[] arr7 = {1, 1, 1, 1, 1};
        int k7 = 2;
        System.out.println("Array: [1, 1, 1, 1, 1], k = 2, Kth smallest (Heap): " + kthFinder.findKthSmallest(arr7, k7));
        System.out.println("Array: [1, 1, 1, 1, 1], k = 2, Kth smallest (Quickselect): " + kthFinder.findKthSmallestQuickselect(arr7.clone(), k7));


        // Edge cases:
        try {
            kthFinder.findKthSmallest(null, 1);
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
            System.out.println("Exception caught: " + e.getMessage());
        }

        try {
            int[] emptyArr = {};
            kthFinder.findKthSmallest(emptyArr, 1);
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
            System.out.println("Exception caught: " + e.getMessage());
        }

        try {
            int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
            kthFinder.findKthSmallest(arr, 4);
        } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
            System.out.println("Exception caught: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}

/*
 * Time and Space Complexity Analysis:
 *
 * findKthSmallest (using PriorityQueue/Max-Heap):
 * - Time Complexity: O(N log K), where N is the size of the array and K is the value of k.
 *   - Iterating through the array takes O(N) time.
 *   - Each offer/poll operation on the max-heap takes O(log K) time.
 * - Space Complexity: O(K), as we store at most K elements in the max-heap.
 *
 * findKthSmallestQuickselect (using Quickselect):
 * - Time Complexity:
 *   - Average Case: O(N) - on average, the partitioning step divides the array into roughly equal parts.
 *   - Worst Case: O(N^2) - occurs when the pivot is consistently the smallest or largest element.  This can be mitigated with better pivot selection (e.g., random pivot or median-of-three).
 * - Space Complexity: O(1) - Quickselect is an in-place algorithm, so it requires only constant extra space. The recursive calls technically take O(log n) space in the call stack for the average case.  This implementation is iterative for O(1) space.
 *
 * Notes:
 * - The Quickselect algorithm modifies the input array. Make sure to clone the array if you need to preserve the original array.
 * - The heap-based approach guarantees O(N log K) time complexity, while Quickselect has a better average-case time complexity of O(N) but a potentially worse worst-case time complexity of O(N^2). For large N and small K, the heap-based approach might be faster. For very large N and K closer to N/2, Quickselect is usually faster in practice (on average).
 * - For production code, Quickselect might be preferred due to its better average-case performance. However, consider adding a random pivot selection or median-of-three pivot selection to mitigate the worst-case O(N^2) scenario.
 */
