 * Time and Space Complexity Analysis:
 *
 * 1. Using Min-Heap:
 *    - Time Complexity: O(n log k), where n is the size of the input array. We iterate through the array once,
 *      and each insertion/removal operation in the min-heap takes O(log k) time.
 *    - Space Complexity: O(k), as we store at most k elements in the min-heap.
 *
 * 2. Using QuickSelect:
 *    - Time Complexity:
 *      - Best/Average Case: O(n), because on average, the partition divides the array into roughly equal parts.
 *      - Worst Case: O(n^2), which occurs when the pivot is consistently the smallest or largest element. To mitigate this,
 *        we use randomized pivot selection.
 *    - Space Complexity: O(1) - in-place algorithm.  However, the recursive calls can add to the call stack. In the worst-case, the recursion depth can be O(n) leading to O(n) space complexity due to the call stack. The average recursion depth is O(log n) though. The iterative version of Quickselect is truly O(1) in space.
 */
