public class TopViewBinaryTree {

    /**
     * Prints the top view of a binary tree.
     *
     * @param root The root of the binary tree.
     */
    public static void printTopView(Node root) {
        if (root == null) {
            return; // Handle empty tree case
        }

        // Use a TreeMap to store nodes at each horizontal distance.
        // TreeMap ensures that the nodes are printed in sorted order of horizontal distances.
        TreeMap<Integer, Integer> topViewMap = new TreeMap<>();

        // Use a queue for level order traversal.  Each element in the queue is a pair
        // of a node and its horizontal distance from the root.
        Queue<Pair> queue = new LinkedList<>();

        // Initialize the queue with the root node and its horizontal distance (0).
        queue.offer(new Pair(root, 0));

        while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
            Pair current = queue.poll();
            Node node = current.node;
            int horizontalDistance = current.horizontalDistance;

            // If this is the first time we've seen this horizontal distance, add the node's
            // data to the map.  This ensures that we only store the topmost node for each
            // horizontal distance.
            if (!topViewMap.containsKey(horizontalDistance)) {
                topViewMap.put(horizontalDistance, node.data);
            }

            // Enqueue the left and right children, if they exist, with their respective
            // horizontal distances (distance - 1 for left, distance + 1 for right).
            if (node.left != null) {
                queue.offer(new Pair(node.left, horizontalDistance - 1));
            }
            if (node.right != null) {
                queue.offer(new Pair(node.right, horizontalDistance + 1));
            }
        }

        // Print the top view nodes in sorted order of horizontal distances.
        for (int data : topViewMap.values()) {
            System.out.print(data + " ");
        }
        System.out.println(); // Add a newline at the end
    }

    // Helper class to store a node and its horizontal distance.
    static class Pair {
        Node node;
        int horizontalDistance;

        Pair(Node node, int horizontalDistance) {
            this.node = node;
            this.horizontalDistance = horizontalDistance;
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Test Case 1: Example Tree
        Node root1 = new Node(1);
        root1.left = new Node(2);
        root1.right = new Node(3);
        root1.left.left = new Node(4);
        root1.left.right = new Node(5);
        root1.right.left = new Node(6);
        root1.right.right = new Node(7);
        System.out.print("Top view of tree 1: ");
        printTopView(root1); // Expected output: 4 2 1 3 7

        // Test Case 2: Skewed Tree (Left)
        Node root2 = new Node(1);
        root2.left = new Node(2);
        root2.left.left = new Node(3);
        root2.left.left.left = new Node(4);
        System.out.print("Top view of tree 2 (skewed left): ");
        printTopView(root2); // Expected output: 4 3 2 1

        // Test Case 3: Skewed Tree (Right)
        Node root3 = new Node(1);
        root3.right = new Node(2);
        root3.right.right = new Node(3);
        root3.right.right.right = new Node(4);
        System.out.print("Top view of tree 3 (skewed right): ");
        printTopView(root3); // Expected output: 1 2 3 4

        // Test Case 4: Single Node Tree
        Node root4 = new Node(1);
        System.out.print("Top view of tree 4 (single node): ");
        printTopView(root4); // Expected output: 1

        // Test Case 5: Empty Tree
        Node root5 = null;
        System.out.print("Top view of tree 5 (empty tree): ");
        printTopView(root5); // Expected output: (nothing printed)

        // Test Case 6: More complex tree
        Node root6 = new Node(5);
        root6.left = new Node(3);
        root6.right = new Node(8);
        root6.left.left = new Node(2);
        root6.left.right = new Node(4);
        root6.right.left = new Node(6);
        root6.right.right = new Node(9);
        root6.right.left.right = new Node(7);
        System.out.print("Top view of tree 6 (complex): ");
        printTopView(root6); // Expected output: 2 3 5 8 9
    }
}

/*
Time Complexity: O(N), where N is the number of nodes in the binary tree.
    - This is because we visit each node exactly once during the level order traversal.
    - TreeMap operations (insertion, retrieval) take O(log K) time in the worst case, where K is the number of unique horizontal distances.  In a balanced tree, K would be approximately N/2. So, the TreeMap operations contribute to O(N log N). However, using a HashMap instead of TreeMap would improve the complexity to O(N) if the horizontal distances did not need to be sorted and printed in order.  However, for the TopView we are required to print from left to right, so the TreeMap is the correct structure here.

Space Complexity: O(W), where W is the maximum width of the binary tree (number of nodes at the widest level).
    - The queue can hold at most all nodes at the widest level of the tree.  In the worst case (a complete binary tree), W can be close to N, but in many cases, it will be less.
    - The TreeMap stores a node for each horizontal distance.  The maximum number of horizontal distances is equal to the width of the tree.

*/
```

