Memoization is a performance optimization technique used to store results of expensive function calls and return the cached result when the same inputs occur again.
Your task is to:
Implement a memoize function in JavaScript.
Use it to wrap any function so that repeated calls with the same arguments return the cached result without recomputation.
Test your memoize implementation with inputs of different data types including numbers, strings, arrays, and objects.
Example 1:
function slowAdd(a, b) {
  console.log("Computing...");
  return a + b;
}

const memoizedAdd = memoize(slowAdd);

console.log(memoizedAdd(2, 3)); // Computing... → 5
console.log(memoizedAdd(2, 3)); // 5 (from cache)
console.log(memoizedAdd(4, 5)); // Computing... → 9
Explanation:
First call with (2, 3) computes and caches the result.
Second call with (2, 3) returns cached value without recomputing.
A different input (4, 5) is computed normally and then cached.
Example 2:
function concatValues(a, b) {
  console.log("Concatenating...");
  return `${a}-${b}`;
}

const memoizedConcat = memoize(concatValues);

console.log(memoizedConcat("Hello", "World")); // Concatenating... → "Hello-World"
console.log(memoizedConcat("Hello", "World")); // "Hello-World" (from cache)
console.log(memoizedConcat([1, 2], [3, 4]));   // Concatenating... → "1,2-3,4"
console.log(memoizedConcat([1, 2], [3, 4]));   // "1,2-3,4" (from cache)
console.log(memoizedConcat({ x: 1 }, { y: 2 })); // Concatenating... → "[object Object]-[object Object]"
Constraints:
The memoization should correctly handle primitive and non-primitive types.
Object and array inputs can be stringified for key generation, but be aware of potential collisions.
Ensure that the memoize function uses closures to store cache privately.

